  "prompt": "What happened at Hirnandani hospital kidney scam? Why scams of other organs are not heard of?",
  "response": "The Hiranandani Hospital kidney scam was a significant medical scandal that came to light in Mumbai, India, around 2016-2017. Here are the key details:\n\nKidney Scam Details:\n1. Multiple doctors and hospital staff were involved in illegally harvesting and selling kidneys\n2. Vulnerable patients, often from low-income backgrounds, were lured with money to donate kidneys\n3. Middlemen and agents were instrumental in finding potential kidney donors and recipients\n4. The scam involved falsifying medical documents to show kidney transplants as legitimate\n5. Patients were told false medical narratives to justify kidney transplantation\n\nRegarding organ scam prevalence:\n1. Kidney scams are more common because:\n- Kidneys can be donated while donor is alive\n- High demand for kidneys due to chronic kidney diseases\n- Easier to extract and transplant compared to other organs\n\n2. Other organ scams do exist but are less frequent due to:\n- More complex transplantation procedures\n- Stricter regulatory mechanisms\n- Most organ transplants require deceased donors\n- Higher medical complications\n\nAuthorities investigated and arrested several individuals involved in the Hiranandani Hospital kidney racket, highlighting the need for stronger medical oversight and ethical practices.",
